Introduction¶

Data Cleaning¶

Upon Visual assessment of my dataset in Microsoft Excel, I realised that my dataset variables has two categories which are records for data recorded after august 2009 and data recorded before 2009. ProsperScore and ProsperRating (Alpha) contain records applicable for data recorded after august 2009.

Firstly, let me convert the ListCreationDate to a datetime data type

In [6]:
#copy original dataset to a new variable for cleaning
loan_clean = loan_data.copy()

#convert the `ListCreationDate` column to a date time datatype
loan_clean['ListingCreationDate']=pd.to_datetime(loan_clean['ListingCreationDate'])
#show the first five date data

Given that the CreditGrade and ProsperRating and Score represents different timeframes of the data, analysis requiring these variables would be done for the different timeframes

Also, the null values in the BorrowerState, Occupation and EmploymentStatus might not pose a threat to our data analysis as they will be replace with Not available for the different variables

And of course, null values in CurrentDeliquencies, AvailableBankCredit and TotalProsperLoans are all statistically correct as not all Borrowers have these variables recorded or available

Next, i want to define a function to replace null values in the categorical variables with Not available

In [7]:
#this function replaces null values with not available
def rep_null(column):
    loan_clean[column].fillna("Not available",inplace=True)
In [8]:
#Applying the function to the desired columns on the data frame
rep_null('BorrowerState')
rep_null('Occupation')

For the EmploymentStatus, replacing the null values with not available will bump up the value of that category already noted in the data set. Since null and not available serves the same meaning, i will do the replacement and proceed with my analysis

listing_Cat = {0:"Not Available",
               1:"Debt Consolidation",
               2:"Home Improvement",
               3:"Business",
               4:"Personal Loan",
               5:"Student Use",
               6:"Auto",
               7:"Other",

               15:"Medical/Dental",
               16:"Motorcycle",
               17:"RV",
               18:"Taxes",
               19:"Vacation",
               20:"Wedding Loans",}
def norm_list(x,y=listing_Cat):
    return y[x]
#renames the column
loan_clean.rename(columns={'ListingCategory (numeric)': 'ListingCategory'},inplace=True)

#applies the user defined function above
loan_clean['ListingCategory'] = loan_clean['ListingCategory'].apply(norm_list)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

This dataset contains 113937 samples of 21 variables. With different data types for the different variables, this data contains records for a loan Company - Prosper. Some of these records are but not limited to the interest rate, loan status, the risk score of each loan and information concerning the borrower.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

Here, i am most eager to find out factors that affect the loan status. also, i am interested in the characteristics of borrowers with high loan amount and how the loan amount is related with its interest rate, that is, does a higher loan amount translate to a better loan in terms of interest rate? Hence, the main features of interest in my dataset are those features that will help to effectively find out the answer to the questions listed above

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The Loan status, BorrowerRate, ProsperScore, Loan Original amount are some of the features that will aid my investigation into the dataset

#define the function that plots an histogram showing the data distribution
def plot_func(column, title, binsize):#title is the proposed 
                                    #title of the chart and binsize specifies the size of the bins in the column
    bins = np.arange(loan_clean[column].min(), loan_clean[column].max()+binsize, binsize)

    loan_clean[column].plot(kind = 'hist', figsize = (7,5), color = "#C13016", bins = bins);#plots a bar chart 
    
    plt.title(label = title, fontsize = 16);#prints the title

Conclusions¶

My main interest was to investigate factors that affect the loan status and how the interest rate relates eith the loan amount taken. From the my investigations, i realized that the relationship between the loan amount and interest rate is not entirely linear as same loan amounts do not have the same interest rate. The Prosper rating serves the same purpose as the prosper score as they both indicate the risk rating of the loan with 1 and AA indicating the best loans in terms of the lowest risk score and HR and 11 indicating loans with high risk scores. Looking at the effect of the Prosper Rating on the relationship between the interest rate and loan amount, i realizeed that the best rating have loans with very high amounts and low interest rates while loans with low ratings have low loan amounts when compared to the best rating's loans plus their interest rates are higher than that of the best ratings's.

limitations¶

  • Any kind of hypothesis testing have not been performed, the basis of this analysis are historical data. Hence, any suggestion for future strategies should be based on a further analysis.
  • Unfortunately, a profile of borrowers was not possible as the findings, according to the current data, does not show any isnightful trend about Porsper borrowers.
  • Many variables present in the original dataset have not been analysed, therefore a more comprehensive analysis should be performed to fill the gaps not covered by the current one.
  • This analysis does not consider socio-economical variables regarding loan applicants that may play a pivotal role in understanding their behaviour. A suggestion for further analysis is to consider more socio-economical and spending behaviour data about borrowers to better profile the most profitable borrowers and target them in marketing campaigns.
